Yes, if this is just your local/dev database and those 10 rows are test data, the simplest approach is:

Drop child table first

Because of the foreign key:

DROP TABLE IF EXISTS fedex_subscribed_accounts;

Then drop parent table

DROP TABLE IF EXISTS fedex_subscriptions;

Or in one go:

DROP TABLE IF EXISTS fedex_subscribed_accounts;
DROP TABLE IF EXISTS fedex_subscriptions;


---

Then clean Flyway history

Check if Flyway has already executed your migration:

SELECT *
FROM flyway_schema_history
ORDER BY installed_rank DESC;

If your migration is something like:

V20_create_tables_fedex_subscription.sql

then either:

Option 1 (Recommended for local)

Delete the entry:

DELETE FROM flyway_schema_history
WHERE version = '20';

Option 2

Run:

./gradlew flywayClean

(if your project allows clean)


---

Then update your DDL

Change the columns to:

customer_id TEXT
registration_id TEXT
subscription_id TEXT
account_number TEXT

Keep:

id UUID
created_at TIMESTAMP
modified_at TIMESTAMP


---

Finally restart application

./gradlew bootRun

or

./gradlew flywayMigrate

Flyway will recreate the tables from scratch using the updated DDL.

Before doing this

Ask yourself:

Is this your local schema only? → Safe to drop.

Is this a shared DEV environment used by the team? → Don't drop; create a new migration instead.


For a first Jira card, if you're unsure, send a quick Teams message:

> "The tables are already created in the dev schema. Since the data is only test data, is it okay if I drop and recreate them with the updated column types, or would you prefer a Flyway alter migration?"



That avoids surprises.